Beating the Averages
Question 1
	The three features of the Lisp language that Graham believes gave his company a completive 
    advantage is a macro, Lisp macros; that allow code to be unique allowing to build complex 
    abstract. Basically, it allows programs that provide an advantage in building complex 
    abstraction and able to solve problems better than other languages. The second feature 
    is the garbage collection that is introduced by Lisp and runtime typing which help remove 
    the need for programmer to write repetitive code and construct less resources logic. 
    These features boost the rapid development in the market and enable them to release 
    software quicker and be able to work with bigger teams. The third features are their so 
    called "secret weapon" that they wrote in a weird AI language with bizarre syntax full of 
    parentheses, which lead most business to avoid it and use the standard tool. 
    Because most competitors or businesses viewed Lisp as more for academic rather than a tool 
    for production, they didn't pay much attention to the language itself which was the source 
    of Viaweb performance.

Question 2
	The two observations that I found most significant in Graham's article is how he talked 
    about the Blub Paradox explaining why many programmers fail to realize they are using 
    a less powerful tool and that "Blub programmer is looking down the power continuum." 
    It is easier to look down on lower language than looking at a higher language and think 
    they don't see the power/use in them. The other observation is when he stated "average 
    performance means that you'll go out of business…" I think that what he means is most 
    average startup fail due to not trying hard enough. Most startups play it safe by using 
    same language, marketing, etc. would lead to an average result in which big companies 
    are likely to achieve it better.  Basically, to survive is to become the odd one to succeed
     in a startup and to do better than everyone else.

